<DOC><DOCNO> AP890319-0066 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1823EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-19 0467</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0476</SECOND><HEAD>Snow in Rockies; Cold in Upper Midwest</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy snow fell Sunday over portions of the Rockies and bittercold weather set records in Michigan and Wisconsin, but most of thenation enjoyed relatively mild, dry weather.   Ten inches of snow fell at the Park West ski area in Utah, and asnow advisory was in effect for elevations above 6,000 feet in theUtah mountains. A snow advisory also was posted for southwestWyoming and the mountains of Colorado.   The tail end of a Pacific storm brought only light precipitationto northern California, but officials there rejoiced that theweekend storm had brought vital rainfall to the drought-plaguedregion.   ``Conditions are still far below normal in too many areas to saythe drought is over,'' said Suzanne Butterfield, statewide droughtcoordinator for the California Department of Water Resources. ``Butit has eased considerably everywhere, with the exception of theCentral Coast and San Joaquin Valley.''   Showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered across thesouth-central United States, but rainfall was generally not heavy.Dry weather prevailed over much of the rest of the country and skieswere fair to partly sunny most places east of the Mississippi.   A cold front in the Southwest brought brisk winds to parts ofSouthern California and a wind advisory was posted for desert andmountain areas. Gusts to 50 mph were reported in the Mojave Desert.   Temperatures were generally below freezing from Montana throughthe Great Lakes region to northern New England, and in the 70s and80s across parts of the Southwest and Southeast.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 19degrees at Grand Forks, N.D., to 88 degrees at Tampa, Fla.   Low temperature records were set in Alpena, Mich., where it was 7below zero; Green Bay, Wis. (5 below); Marquette, Mich. (11 below);Muskegon, Mich. (5 degrees); Rochester, Minn. (5 below); andTraverse City, Mich. (4 below).   The forecast for Monday included snow over the central highplains and the Great Lakes, scattered snow showers over the centralplateau and the central Rockies and rain from western Kansas andnorthwestern Texas through the lower and middle Mississippi Valleyto the Appalachians. Fair to partly sunny skies were expected acrossthe rest of the nation.   High temperatures were expected to be below 50 from the northernhalf of the plateau region through the northern and central plainsto New England; in the upper teens to lower 30s from eastern Montanathrough the upper Mississippi Valley to upper Michigan and acrossnorthern Maine; into the 70s from southern and central California tosouthwestern New Mexico and from southern and central Texas toFlorida and southern Georgia; and in the 80s in south central Texasand across the Florida peninsula.</TEXT></DOC>